8.  Standardizing Check Formats. Activities include 

(i)  consultant prepares a draft standardized check; 
(ii)  review standard and have PPU comment (2 weeks); 
(iii)  consultant reviews PPU comments and resubmits proposal (1 week); 
(iv)  further review by PPU (1 week); 
(v)  consultant incorporates any comments, and PPU then reviews the draft with 
other NBC departments; 
(vi)  incorporate comments from other NBC departments (1 week); 
(vii)  review draft as agreed by NBC with the Bankers Association (1 week); 
(viii)  PPU incorporates comments from the Bankers Association (1 week); 
(ix)  PPU prepares draft prakas (including translation) for approval, if appropriate  
(1 month); 
(x)  PPU solicits comments from other NBC departments on draft prakas (2 weeks); 
(xi)  PPU incorporates any further comments (1 week); and. 
(xii)  seek agreement from NBC management to issue the prakas. 

9.  Developing a Large-Value Electronic Payment System. Activities include 

(i)  PPU and other NBC departments review user requirements over 4 weeks, with 
consultant incorporating comments over a week (4 weeks); 
(ii)  analyze  type  of  communication  network  to  be  used—SWIFT  or  dedicated 
telecommunication lines 
−  consultant to prepare initial analysis over 1 month (4 weeks), 
−  PPU reviews consultant’s report and offers suggestions (2 weeks), 
−  consultant incorporates comments from PPU (2 days), 
−  PPU reviews the report with other NBC departments (1 week), 
−  consultant prepares final proposal (1 week), and 
−  PPU seeks approval for communication infrastructure to support agreed 
system (2 weeks); 
(iii)  consultant  updates  user  requirements  with  communications  infrastructure  
(1 week), reviews the approach with the Bankers Association and amend as 
needed (2 weeks), and seeks approval to develop a request for proposal (RFP) 
for soliciting bids from vendors (3 weeks); 
(iv)  consultant  develops  an  RFP  for  soliciting  bids  according  to  approved 
procurement guidelines 
(a)  consultant reviews RFP with PPU (4 weeks); 
(b)  consultant incorporates comments from PPU (1 week); 
(c)  consultant and PPU develop list of potential vendors (3 weeks);  
(d)  consultant  establishes  evaluation  criteria  and  develops  appropriate 
weights for each criterion, incorporating these in RFP (2–3 weeks);  
(e)  consultant and PPU establish the evaluation team and begin the training 
process (1 week); 
(f)  PPU seeks approval to issue RFP (3 weeks); and

      Appendix 5  59 
(g)  issue RFP and respond to vendor inquiries over 2 months, being sure to 
maintain a equal access for all vendors (8 weeks); 
(v)  evaluation team evaluates responses to RFP 
(a)  each  member  reads  and  rates  each  response  independently,  and 
documents their conclusions (3 weeks); 
(b)  consultant takes the independent evaluations and analyses the findings 
(1 week); 
(c)  evaluation  team  reviews  the  consultant’s  report  and  proposes 
amendments (1 week); 
(d)  consultant incorporates suggestions (2 days); 
(e)  consultant identifies three vendors (short list) to seek further information 
about their response, with the process documented to show why the 
vendors were selected (2 weeks); 
(f)  evaluation  team  reviews  consultant’s  report  and  offers  suggestions  
(1 week); 
(g)  consultant finalizes report (2 days), then circulates report to those who 
need be informed (1 week); 
(h)  evaluation team visits the short-listed vendors or the short-listed vendors 
are invited to make a more detailed presentation to the team (3 weeks). 
(i)  each  team  member  rates  each  vendor  independently  and  documents 
their findings (2 days); 
(j)  consultant  prepares  a  detailed  report  to  support  the  selected  vendor  
(1 week); 
(k)  evaluation team  makes detailed presentation to management to seek 
approval to negotiate a contract with the selected vendor (3 weeks); 
(l)  evaluation team and the consultant conduct contract negotiations with the 
preferred vendor (2–3 months); 
(m)  evaluation team reviews the vendor’s proposed design against the user 
requirements to ensure all requirements will be met (2 weeks); 
(n)  vendor amends design to meet user requirements if necessary (2 weeks); 
and 
(o)  the contract is approved and signed (2 weeks); 
(vi)  during implementation, the vendor must provide a project plan based on the 
negotiated  contract  (1  month);  full  implementation,  overseen  by  an 
implementation team including both vendor and NBC representatives, will likely 
take at least a year; and 
(vii)  the NBC consultant should be capable of developing and documenting user 
requirements, building consensus among NBC staff and the bankers, preparing 
the RFP for the system under appropriate procurement guidelines, identifying a 
list of possible vendors to respond to the RFP, training and leading the evaluation 
team,  assisting  in  evaluating  responses,  reviewing  the  final  vendors  and 
documenting as to why one should be selected over another, participating in the 
negotiation of the contract, reviewing in-depth the vendor’s solution with the user 
requirements and identifying areas that do not meet the requirements, seeking 
solutions  to  the  shortfall  in  requirements,  monitoring  implementation  of  the 
vendor’s product, training staff in the operation of the new system, training and 
educating  bankers  and  other  users  in  the  functions  of  the  system,  assuring 
successful production environment, and coordinating with senior management 
and maintaining their confidence in the project.
